ğŸ’³ Why Credit Cards Are Called the Most Profitable Bank Product

| Topic             | Explanation                                                                                    |
| ----------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Main reason       | Credit cards generate revenue from multiple sources (interest, fees, transaction commissions). |
| Interest income   | Banks earn interest when customers donâ€™t pay the full bill and carry a balance.                |
| Fees charged      | Annual fees, late payment fees, over-limit fees, foreign transaction fees, etc.                |
| Merchant payments | Merchants pay a fee for every credit-card transaction processed.                               |
| Result            | Multiple revenue streams make credit cards one of the most profitable banking products.        |

ğŸŒ How Visa / Mastercard Make Money

| Revenue Source  | Explanation                                                                                         |
| --------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Network fees    | Charge issuing and acquiring banks for using their payment network.                                 |
| Assessment fees | Small percentage charged on every transaction routed through their network.                         |
| Processing fees | Fixed fee per transaction for authorization and settlement.                                         |
| Role            | They donâ€™t issue cards or lend money â€” they run the payment network connecting banks and merchants. |

ğŸ’° Credit Card Payment Flow Economics (Example: $100 Purchase)

| Step | Who Involved                        | What Happens                                       | Money Flow                                              |
| ---- | ----------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| 1    | Cardholder â†’ Merchant               | Customer buys product worth $100 using credit card | Merchant receives payment via card network              |
| 2    | Merchant                            | Accepts credit card for higher sales               | Pays Merchant Discount Rate (MDR)                       |
| 3    | Acquiring Bank (Merchantâ€™s bank)    | Processes payment for merchant                     | Keeps small markup fee (example: $0.25)                 |
| 4    | Issuing Bank (Customerâ€™s card bank) | Provided credit card to customer                   | Earns interchange fee (example: $1.75)                  |
| 5    | Card Network (Visa/Mastercard)      | Routes transaction between banks                   | Charges network fee (example: ~0.11% + fixed fee)       |
| 6    | Cardholder â†’ Issuing Bank           | Customer repays bank                               | Bank earns interest/late fees if balance not paid fully |
